<rating>1<//rating>< text>
They have forever lost my business. I bought my wife a Lady's Smith 357 at the Costa Mesa gun show and of course it's busy and we were passed off several times to various people until we finally got all the paperwork done. I'd say I took about an hour from start to finish. Now the wait is on. The reason for the purchase was we were planning a range day trip of about eight friends up to some property in Campo and we were really excited to try out this new pistol. We had plenty of time to get the gun since we cod pick it up after the ten day hold. We get it Tuesday and we can get a new holster and a few other things so she can be comfortable with her new gun. Ten days comes and goes so we jump in the car and drive up to the Mira Mar store but when we get there they can't find the gun. Actually they can't even find the paperwork let alone the almost $800 gun. So about 40 minutes later we get the "I'll call you tomorrow" line. Well tomorrow comes and goes and still nothing. I waited another day and still got nothing. I call back and nobody knows what going on with the missing gun and paperwork. Well of course I'm not real happy with the lack of customer service and so I start calling the other branches to try and get ahold of a manage or regional manager that can get me some answers. No one can help so I call the San Diego branch again and got some really nice guy that seemed to care and he promised me that someone would call me right away. That was the best service I received from this company. About five minutes later I got some guy with an attitude and very unapologetic call me and say he was the general manager. He said they were shorthanded and they didn't know were the gun was because it never got unloaded from the Costa Mesa gun show. He said all the paperwork was fine and the background check was good but the gun was sent to the Las Vegas Shot show. How does this happen? Yeah, just "short handed", not sorry? Not what I wanted to hear. I get a call back from the one guy that was helpful and asked if I wanted to cancel the transaction but I'd eat the almost $40 that goes to the state so I said no. He told me he would have the gun Monday and I'd get a call when it came in. Of course we didn't get to take it to range day so there's that, and wouldn't you know it, no call on Monday. I finally called on Tuesday and had to explain everything again to the guy on the phone and he said "bummer". Well yeah this has been a major bummer. My wife picked up the gun on Thursday since she was in the area and they offered her a 10% discount on ammo when she was there. That's not how you fix this colossal screw up on your part. I was warned by several of my friends that have had their own bad experiences with ammo bros but I made the mistake of not listening. Listen to this, I will never use ammo bros again. One star for the guy that helped, thanks dude<//text>

< review>
It was Independence Day and I thought to myself, today has to be the day I buy my first firearm. The employees there were immediately welcoming. I was helped by Yvette and she guided me through the steps of buying my first weapon. Took my handgun safety test. Passed with flying colors! A man named Jeff B. provided me with a lot of info about which gun I should first own. Incredibly helpful and kind, even with my total lack of knowledge. He told me, go with a handgun that YOU like, because if you don't like the gun, you won't shoot it. So, I took his advice and got a brand new Springfield XD40. My entire visit lasted about 1.5 hours. And there was not one second where I felt lost or unwelcome. All the employees are very knowledgeable from their own experiences. This store will definitely be my go-to store from now on. And I would definitely recommend to everyone.< /review>

< Review>
It's rare that I spend the time to write a review, but my recent experience with this store have left such a negative impression on me that I feel I am obligated to share my encounter with any future potential patron.  I have been going to this particular branch of Ammo Bros for years since it is located fairly close to my residence.  In the past, the staff has generally been very helpful, the items variety stocked was great and I enjoy the overall clean and efficient layout of the store.  I did plenty of PPT and DROS transaction at this store as well as loading up on cleaning supplies and ammunitions.  My latest experience with this store, however, graduated from a minor inconvenience to possibly outright the worst retail experience I have ever had.

I purchased a firearm from out of state and had it shipped to this branch of Ammo Bros for DROS.  FedEX confirmed the firearm arrive on Monday but I couldn‚Äôt start the DROS until Friday due to the fact that they couldn‚Äôt find the firearm.  The staff has said that the gun was likely shipping to their HQ nearby and they simply did not have it on site.  This, while irksome, was anything worth complaining about.

When it came time to pick up my firearm, I was serviced by a young Asian gentleman.  The way he handled my firearm was simply unacceptable.  Without asking for permission, he manhandled and toyed with my rifle with absolutely no regards.  At one point, he used metal of his ball point pen, push against one of the welded pins of my rifle.  For what purpose he did this, I still do not understand.  A brand new $2,000+ firearm and he left a blemish on the finish simply for his amusement.  He then put the butt of the rifle on the floor then tried to remove the welded muzzle device.  The staff proceed to play games with my firearms, taking it around their facility, shouldering it.  At one point, the staff hid the rifle and took another rifle from their shelf to prank one another.  The entire pickup process lasted over 45 minutes.

Ammo Bro used to be one of my favorite FFL due to their great customer service, knowledgeable staff, and great products selections.  My most recent experience left me flabbergasted and I have a very hard time recommending anyone to go to their Ontario store.< /Review>

< Text>
Relic Vintage is quite literally the store of my dreams; I never knew something so perfect could actually exist until I walked in and saw it all for myself. To start I'd like to say the clothing selection is amazing. Every piece there is desirable and beautiful and made at a high standard that is quite frankly missing in clothing nowadays. I got chills from touching some of the gorgeous pieces. I could definitely spend hours in this store simply marveling at everything. For women there is a generous selection of pieces ranging from beautiful party dresses to irresistible pedal pusher capris. As I was browsing, my mouth agape, I was immediately approached by Oran and he started a dressing room for me. Oran gave me the best service, by far, that I've ever had at a store. I'd find a pair of pants and he'd know just the thing that would go with him. He brought me countless beautiful party dresses to try on and very single one of them fit me perfectly and were something that I loved and would pick out myself. And same for the friend I was with. He appears to have a talent for figuring out people's size and taste in dress without even asking. I wish everyone who worked in stores were like Oran. I will definitely be returning very soon. If you have a chance to go to Relic Vintage, do not pass it up! Everything about this store is unbelievably amazing.</Text>

< text>
Relic Vintage is unlike any other vintage store that I have ever been to and I am a diehard vintage-enthusiast. The selection is impeccable, curated by the fabulous owner, Oran, who has an eye for top quality vintage and prices his pieces affordably. I think the best part about shopping here is knowing that Oran will take the time to fit you into a perfect look and provide a unique shopping experience. I wish he could be my personal stylist! So many times, I have gone into vintage stores only to feel like I was rummaging at a yard sale and that is NOT the case here. Everything is in really good shape because Oran is a tailor, as well, and can fix any piece! Amazing! In fact, there was one dress I had my eye on but was far too tight, and he was able to transform it to fit me perfectly. I cannot recommend Relic Vintage enough! I tell all of my friends and family to shop here and bring my girls in for a fun time trying on clothes. In fact, Oran fitted out my bridesmaids for my wedding and they all looked AMAZING.< /text>

<Gmap_id>0x80e913b496586359:0x1f0961e9cbde7901< /Gmap_id><userid>101611669214591870404</userid>< review>
In my quest for the perfect veggie sandwich I recently stopped by Panino's. I'm not vegetarian but I love a good veggie sammich.

They have a pretty good selection of vegetarian offerings, so I went with the Mixed Veggie Sandwich- Marinated sun-dried tomatoes, roasted red peppers, artichoke hearts, greens, and a few other tasty toppings.

It wasn't the absolute best veggie sandwich I've had, but it was pretty good. All fresh, quality ingredients.

The staff was friendly, and my food was ready in minutes. They are on the pricey side for a sandwich, but really about average for an upscale deli.

I'll be back.<//review>

<response>None</response><userid>107981767706731392463< /userid><pictures>None</pictures><date>1577832760682</date>< Review>
I've been going to this place since I was a kid. I'm still going as an adult, which says a lot. When I was a kid I didn't really have much of a say over which bagel place we went to nor did I really care. I just wanted a bagel, it didn't matter where I was getting that bagel, unless I had to go super far away for that bagel or if it was a place that didn't specialize in making bagels. Like if I got a bagel from a place that mainly sells burritos or pho and they sold bagels on the side...that probably wouldn't be a great bagel. Pretty much my criteria as a kid for bagels was a place that was close and specialized in making bagels. The Daily Bagel Cafe has both of those things. It's only a 10 min drive away and you know they specialize in making bagels if "bagel" is literally part of their name.

As I got older, I started making more decisions for myself, which meant trying other bagels from other bagel shops. Throughout my lifetime I've tried many bagels from many different bagel shops. Even after going through so many other bagels, I still think Daily Bagel Cafe has the best bagels. They were my favorite when I was a kid, they are my favorite now, and they'll probably be my favorite till I die.< /Review>

<date>1562771896870</date>< Review>
Always go here for bagels whenever I get a craving.
Their selection is great, and they have many different bagel and spread combinations you could choose from.
I personally favor their jalapeno cream cheese and their onion, jalapeno, jala-cheddar, everything, and garlic bagels.
You also can get the bagels toasted twice for crispiness before digging in.
Get in early, if you arrive after 11 on the weekend their selection is usually sparse.
They open early and are always kind to the customer.
Definite must for anyone in or visiting Morgan Hill.<//Review>

<userid>112088648243033467161< /userid>< Name>
Chelsea E<//Name>
<time>1615165442537< /time><Rate>4< /Rate>< Text>
The pros of living at Avana: the staff is super nice and helpful! The units look really nice and updated. They pretty much have all the amenities that you need, such as a dishwasher, washer & dryer, microwave, and garbage disposal. I do wish the washer was a bit bigger, because it is super tiny, but at least it has one so that is very nice! I also feel quite safe here, because it is gated and you need a fob to get into the building and garage. I had once left a package in front of my door overnight and it did not get stolen! :) (but you could also ask the staff to put it into your unit with your permission). They also provide parcel pending, which means your package will be left in a secured box, so that is handy too! I can't tell you much yet about the building amenities that they offer, since they are closed due to covid.

The cons: the windows and ceilings could definitely be improved. I can hear every single move my upstairs neighbor makes (I can even hear him/her open up a drawer), so that is quite annoying. Next, the windows are super thin, so you hear every single noise that is outside. You live right in the center of LB (which is a huge plus(!) because the area is really nice), so it can definitely get noisy outside. Sadly there is a pupper outside that likes to bark for two hours straight around 4/5am, and that makes it really hard to sleep through. If they had updated their windows and ceilings (and if I'm very greedy: a pool), Avana would be perfect!<//Text>

<Response>None< /Response>< Text>
The lake here is great. However after camping here for several nights I can safely say we won't be camping here again. This campground was definitely a party area. Which is fine, if that's what you're looking for. If you want to enjoy nature and are looking for a peaceful place to enjoy a relaxing evening under the stars, this ain't it. Every night we were here there were multiple sites  blaring a variety of music until about 2:30AM. When we mentioned it to the park rangers we were told to call 911 when it happens and report it, or we could move campsites. Drinking is usually accompanied with loud music at all hours and it shows. Beer bottles, cans, and other liquor containers are strewn up and down the streets in the morning. And the bathroom had vomit all over toilets and floors in the restrooms. I know this isn't the fault of the park rangers or people running the camp ground and it's really disappointing to see people treat a public area with such disrespect. However, if they enforced their rules, which you have to agree to when reserving a camp space, I can't help but feel like some of this wouldn't happen.<//Text>

Luis Hernandez</name>
< date>
1620398493134< /date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
It was awesome going to Lake Perris. It is a big Lake. The place is huge, with its camping grounds, and different hiking/biking trails. No Dogs in the water, but you can take them on the campgrounds.

We took our boat, and it was great, with 3 huge launching ramps, it was hassle free. Going back around the 21st of May, for my wife's birthday, and camp there over night.

And it's secure, Sheriffs make there presence known, by their constant patroling and safety checks.

It was a great family time, that is why we will be going back in 3 weeks.<//Text>

Jacqueline Houts<//user_name>
< Date>
1621825168590< /Date>
< Rating>
3< /Rating>
< Review>
The lake here is great. However after camping here for several nights I can safely say we won't be camping here again. This campground was definitely a party area. Which is fine, if that's what you're looking for. If you want to enjoy nature and are looking for a peaceful place to enjoy a relaxing evening under the stars, this ain't it. Every night we were here there were multiple sites  blaring a variety of music until about 2:30AM. When we mentioned it to the park rangers we were told to call 911 when it happens and report it, or we could move campsites. Drinking is usually accompanied with loud music at all hours and it shows. Beer bottles, cans, and other liquor containers are strewn up and down the streets in the morning. And the bathroom had vomit all over toilets and floors in the restrooms. I know this isn't the fault of the park rangers or people running the camp ground and it's really disappointing to see people treat a public area with such disrespect. However, if they enforced their rules, which you have to agree to when reserving a camp space, I can't help but feel like some of this wouldn't happen.</Review>

< Review>
It was awesome going to Lake Perris. It is a big Lake. The place is huge, with its camping grounds, and different hiking/biking trails. No Dogs in the water, but you can take them on the campgrounds.

We took our boat, and it was great, with 3 huge launching ramps, it was hassle free. Going back around the 21st of May, for my wife's birthday, and camp there over night.

And it's secure, Sheriffs make there presence known, by their constant patroling and safety checks.

It was a great family time, that is why we will be going back in 3 weeks.< /Review>

<Review>It has a long beach front fairly shaded with trees. Beach and boat launch run 1.5 miles. There are 8 parking sections total but 2 are closed. The far parking section 8 leads to a beach section with a large grassy area.  All the sections have clean restroom stalls and outdoor showers. They are all open and working. The entrance fee for day use is 10 dollars. Boats may be more. There are no concessions nor food stands at all. The park has ample shade trees all up and down the beach. It is a good park for a day outing on a hot day. I can't comment on boating on the lake as I don't boat. They should have paddle board and kayak rentals places but I don't see anything like that there.< /Review>< Gmap_id>

<Review>This lake has many nice views from the mountains to the lake and a view into the city if your into that. The water looks clean from a distance but I havent gone close enough to see how clean the lake is since I mainly go for biking. There is a nice asphalt trail that circles all around the lake and you can even ride on the dam, as well as walk or run. My only gripe is some of the tables along the asphalt trail are poorly taken care of with grass taking over the table which causes some stops to be infested with flying bugs but most of them are fine. Overall it's a nice lake and it's worth a visit if you want to ride a bike, walk, run, ride a horse, or even use boats, jet skies, or canoes to use in the lake.< /Review>< pics>

< text>
This is my favorite lake until the moment, even when it is an artificial lake you do not feel it. The place is surrounded by nature, grass fields, beach sand and animals like squirtles and seagles. You have picnic areas, bbq grillers areas even a camping area. If you like fishing there is a part you can do it but honestly i never tried. Strongly recommended for families and people who like quiet places. The fee (without a boat) is only 10 usd.< /text>

<Date>1570412424514< /Date><rate>5< /rate>< Text>
Beautiful state park. It cost $8 or $10 to park. You can camp, fish, boat, hike, even ride horses. There are places to shower, full toilet and even a convenient store that sells bait. Park rangers, DFG, and police all have stations there. 50mph on water I believe. 2 sand beaches for swimming. Dogs are welcome.</Text>

< text>
I liked each spot to camp had a water spicket and restrooms close by. Campgrounds are very clean when we went and the only issue I had was with check in. I didn't know that even though you made a reservation you still have to check in and register your vehicle before you go into the campgrounds. Granted, supposedly there were signs but a lot of people got confused and had to reform into the long check-in line. It got bottlenecked at that point because of so many people trying to check in at once, but overall we really enjoyed the spot.<//text>

0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e< /gmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
<Text>We came to the lake for a field visit with grandpa and the dog. According to Google, the place was expected to be crowded - given the time of the year and historical trends. I am glad the flow was incorrect, as the lake was empty and the grounds incredibly clean. We could take the dog for a long hike, and she had a blast playing fetch by herself. Throughout our few hours there, we only saw a couple of other visitors, which is strange given the place is marvelous, and there are plenty of nearby municipalities. This is a location I would recommend during weekdays because of its laud public, yet we were lucky to find a weekend that was too cold for other people. There are portable throughout the hikes and a few benches for the elders to sit. Some decent picture-spot for birds are also along the pathway. Although comprehensive because of the weather, we saw minimal wildlife around - other than a few ducks on the lake. Around the ducks, there were fishermen with short-throw rods. Strangely, many of the different parking zones were closed, thus some combined flow was created. On a second note, it would be nice to have some snack machines for people who forgot to bring their food. There are large, permanent toilets nearby the docking station, but they lacked a functioning hand dryer and some soap.<//Text>< Pics>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMbFJgQgIchE11Qax_-Bcw-H7TUGpdyv1SsyWKm=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>

<user_id>109804766746365052622<//user_id><username>Cameron F< /username>< time>
1523860935357</time>
<Rate>4< /Rate><review>I have camped at Lake Perris twice. I highly recommend visiting even for a day trip. Camping reservations are easily done online. The CA State Ranger said weekend camping fills up during the peak summer months. I stayed midweek in June without an issue.

Camping in April was good & bad. The good is better weather (low 80's) and few people. The bad was more insects. A swarm of gnats plagued us. I don't remember any bug problems in June, just hotter temperatures (90's).

The lake is great. The water was a little chilly in April but my family still got in the water. The water was a perfect cool temperature in June.

There are built bathrooms at both the lake and can't ground. There are free showers in the campground bathrooms. Bring your own soap. There are water facets near the camping roads to do dishes and such. I always being water to drink. There are fire pits at each campsite.<//review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPOQtW-sznjpp0SUdF2_oeiNzRL-OjrFRdkQSrm=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMLM4MSVRb7Vw7Tzkl7ydgp6gZNgFs8oNM9V8Ak=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNKMug-fJ3tJUt2RsGZJYuzgM3qhTq1y_Qn89i8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPVV4fa5HJsF064-HyUYvdekk53FrnnGGgqQZ9D=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNIRbrE9FnL9464Gb_G3Z9T64SM4EsHvJ4PWi_b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><Response>None< /Response><Gmap_id>0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e<//Gmap_id></record>

Daniel Hampen< /user_name>
<date>1570412424514<//date><rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Beautiful state park. It cost $8 or $10 to park. You can camp, fish, boat, hike, even ride horses. There are places to shower, full toilet and even a convenient store that sells bait. Park rangers, DFG, and police all have stations there. 50mph on water I believe. 2 sand beaches for swimming. Dogs are welcome.< /Review>

<Pics>None<//Pics><user>115122112734850417410<//user><user_name>Michael Hosking< /user_name><Text>Very nice State of California campground, park and lake.  The campground is nice with a lot of spots both dry camping and with hookups but lack sewer hookups.  They have several ADA spots that are available for service connected Veterans and Veterans also get free day use, camp spots and lake use after they apply for their Veterans application with the state.  My overall grade is a B, and only due to shallow camp spots and curbing that limits larger campers and makes it difficult to get in and out of their campground spots.</Text></record></dataset><record>
<user_name>Claudia G</user_name>< Response>

< review>
I loved getting away for a day here there is a $10 entry fee so bring some cash it's worth it. This was my first time and there's so many different parking areas with access to the lake you can drive further down to be around less people. Probably wanna make sure you bring food and drinks cuz there's nothing available to purchase close by. But they do have benches, grass areas with trees for shade, bathrooms, and a nice area by the water with a thicker sand. I believe the parks for kids was still closed. And just a little tip it's a good idea to bring a sun hat cuz the water feels so good you wanna be in it the entire time but the sun is so strong I was lucky to have a nice big sun üëí hat. They also have camping areas there I wanna camp there soon ‚ù§. There are some üêü fishes that occasionally swim close by the shore but its honestly cool to see so close I was nervous at first but you get over it üòÇ. All in all it was a great time i highly recommend it< /review>

<gmap_id>0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e<//gmap_id><date>1558646997721<//date><review>In the past Lake perris was known for a not so clean recreational Campground/lake. The water was drained,so repairs could be done on the Dam,and it also helped create more plants/trees for fish to hide around,and take our lures. I only started going back last year. Since last april they have added more water,and is very close to its 100% capacity,the Restrooms,water,beaches,and camp areas are cleaner and clearer. weekdays are great to go fishing,BBQ, or anything you do there to have a good time. The weekdays are great if you want a nice quiet time,with friends,family,Both or even alone. There is ussuly 1-3 boats on the water. Now the weekends are different,and holidays. The marina still rents out boats that are kinda beat up,and the price is high per hour. The Lake now allows you fish from the dock. For a fee of course, $2 for kids $3 for adults. The price for park entry is $10 for the day,camping is separate price. The Lake also offers hiking and a paved trail that wraps around the lake for Bike riding,or running.the South end of the lake has a small area to picnic,camp and fish. At one time you could swim,but i would not recommend it. Only because people fish and it has alot more broken bushes that you can not see since the water level raised. If anyone has any questions feel free to ask me and i will answer as soon as i see them. I have been going to lake perris for over 20 years. I moved to moreno valley in 1985,moved away in 2003.< /review>< Rate>
5</Rate>

<user>110464121532125400431<//user><time>1618510200994< /time><user_name>David Price< /user_name>< text>
Clean, reminded me of back home.<//text>
<Response>None</Response>< Gmap_id>
0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e</Gmap_id>
<Rate>5<//Rate></record></dataset><record>
<UserId.>114321939641171568786</UserId.>< Name>
jesse A.</Name>
<date>1595181482125< /date><Rate>3<//Rate>< Review>
Make sure you get there by 7am; there will be a long line to get in. I arrived at 10 and had to wait 50 minutes to get to the pay booth ( the park is worth the wait). It costs10 bucks to get in for a daily visit. If you have a boat, your wait will be longer because the state officials need to inspect your vessel for foreign entities on your boat surface.

I found lot 9 to be the cleanest and parking was accessible; make sure when you pick your tree to camp under the shade,  to place your belongings around the tree so no one will come later on and highjack your afternoon shade. Yes, people will actually do that, it happened to us. Lots 1,4,9 and 10 were the only beaches open on 7/18/2020. There will be about a 75 yard walk from your car to the sand,  but in my case, it was quite exhausting carrying out our stuff to and from the camp to the car.

Then there's the bathroom; the one close to us was terrible; the sewer line was backed up allowing a puddle of sewer water in the center of  both the men's and woman's. That problem was not fixed during our stay,  we had to walk to the next available restroom which was clean. You can grill carne asada, but make sure you toss your coal in the appropriate containers located close to the restrooms.

The water was breath taking, relaxing and refreshing considering I come from a 115 degree climate. As for Covid,  according to CDC rules for the county of Riverside,   you don't have to wear your mask unless you leave your camp and are closer than 6 feet from someone else. Unfortunately,  I only saw about 5 people wearing a mask outside their camp. No one was wearing a mask in the restroom; if anyone should be wearing a mask, it's in a bathroom right?

I will return to this lake, but only for a weekend stay, because it's not worth all the work for a daily stay. Anyways, I hope this helps and have fun.  Remember to be safe.<//Review>

< review>
It was such a nice day today , so I decided to go to Lake Perris. There was so few people there. So peaceful and quiet. I took a lunch with me and then did some walking. The area was clean. Some spots were closed to enter. I was told dogs are allowed but not near the sand area and then they have to remain on a leash. Would be nice to take the dog for a long walk there.
Price is $10 a day all day.</review>

< rating>
5< /rating>
<Review>This place is like an oasis in the desert. Quail loop 1-44 site number 4 (handicap placard required by anyone in the group) $30 per night, $10 per additional vehicle not legally towed. If you're bringing a boat PLEASE BRING IT SUPER DRY AND SUPER CLEAN! I can't stress that enough in case you get someone inspecting it who's as thorough as they're supposed to be, then you can't bring your boat in the lake. They might check your motor, carpet, fishing lures, even draining pipes for the slightest hint of moisture. Or you might get someone chill who just does a quick once over and passes you. Either way don't risk it and take a day to really clean and dry your boat so you don't lug it around for nothing. Don't put drinks or ice chest in your boat prior to inspection! There is a charge for boating like $8. So other than that enjoy the clean lake and beautiful views of mountains, the quails, coyotes, squirrels and road runners are fun to look at.</Review>< userid>
103773287852056773267</userid>

C. J.P.E.< /username>

</record></dataset><record>
<text>For whatever reason, the staff at this lake are just terrible. Wait times for the gate in the morning are always long, the fee collection takes longer than DVL and other nearby lakes, and the boat inspectors are unnecessarily strict in their duties. I've had one ranger threaten to fail my inspection for "moisture around the drain of my cooler" and have had another inspector ask me to leave the boat as I was putting gear away while he was doing an inspection for a re-entry tag on my way out.

It's also a free for all for the jetskis and wake boats during the summer here. Damn dlshame because Perris is a fun lake to fish.<//text>< Name>
Chris Rhoden<//Name>

Michael Seely< /name>
< Date>
1561320996678</Date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
I love Lake Perris. There is swimming and sailing and boating and my favorite FISHING!!! They have a beach that is just for swimming and my kids love it!!! The fishing we haven't found what I would call a good spot yet but I have only fished from the shore and only a couple spots. Years ago I use to catch lots of fish. When they had the lake drained they built lots of spawning areas for the pan fish, bass and blue gills, they also created lots of catfish hiding/living areas. Should be excellent fishing real real soon!!!! Oh and they have camping!! Its awesome!! I love it!!< /Review>

< username>
numa Quintanilla< /username>
</record></dataset><record>
< Text>
I've been here many times with family and friends. It's great! Visiting the lake: Make sure you bring a shade tent and chairs because if you plan to sit next to the water there is absolutely no shade. Also it's a good 10 minute walk from the picnic tables to the water. It's almost impossible to wheel anything to the water because of the fine sand (coolers, strollers..etc). Camping: Very fun here! Spots are large. They have a lot of bathrooms that are well kept. Cart drives around selling firewood and ice in the evening. Lots of trees. It's a great spot to relax and be outdoors. Pet friendly! They have a 10pm silent time set and there is security that drives around enforcing rules. As always, no glass. I HIGHLY recommend this place!!</Text>

< Review>
It's a perfect getaway from the big city and it's located like 1hour and 25 min from Los Angeles. They have a lake to visit for the day and also camping grounds. They have two different campgrounds one for people who just want to camp with a tent and another for the RV and we stayed at the RV place without an RV and was 15 dollars more , 45 for RV section and 30 just for tents. But best part about the RV section it has electricity and water. You can come and go as you please the gates always open and staff and park rangers very helpful. It is a walk to the lake though. But the campground have benches, fire pits, restroom and shower. It's very clean too. They allow boats and jet skies on the lake too</Review>

< Time>
1556524702056< /Time>
< rate>
5</rate>
<Text>I've been here many times with family and friends. It's great! Visiting the lake: Make sure you bring a shade tent and chairs because if you plan to sit next to the water there is absolutely no shade. Also it's a good 10 minute walk from the picnic tables to the water. It's almost impossible to wheel anything to the water because of the fine sand (coolers, strollers..etc). Camping: Very fun here! Spots are large. They have a lot of bathrooms that are well kept. Cart drives around selling firewood and ice in the evening. Lots of trees. It's a great spot to relax and be outdoors. Pet friendly! They have a 10pm silent time set and there is security that drives around enforcing rules. As always, no glass. I HIGHLY recommend this place!!</Text><Pics>None<//Pics>< Resp>
None<//Resp>

<text>I've been here many times with family and friends. It's great! Visiting the lake: Make sure you bring a shade tent and chairs because if you plan to sit next to the water there is absolutely no shade. Also it's a good 10 minute walk from the picnic tables to the water. It's almost impossible to wheel anything to the water because of the fine sand (coolers, strollers..etc). Camping: Very fun here! Spots are large. They have a lot of bathrooms that are well kept. Cart drives around selling firewood and ice in the evening. Lots of trees. It's a great spot to relax and be outdoors. Pet friendly! They have a 10pm silent time set and there is security that drives around enforcing rules. As always, no glass. I HIGHLY recommend this place!!< /text>< gmap_id>

< Time>
1569957600721<//Time>
< rate>
4< /rate>
< review>
It's nearly the "parking lot" style camping experience at the "hook up" sites. Not completely, but close.
They have everything for the full hook ups except no 50amp (where I was parked) and no sewer drain at the drains in the camp site. Grey only. They do have the dump stations on the way out with all you'll need at the 3 position  dumps. The staff is about as friendly as anyone that doesn't want to talk and deals with their job, for the most part. I can only explain for the one guy that wasn't unpleasant, wasn't friendly bus was friendly, and wasn't pleasant..... He was just THERE.
It's a bit of a walk to the lake. Nothing serious, just through a small field, past the main 25MPH road that some people think it's a 55mph road and through the grass area through the picnic and..... WHEW! I'M TIRED JUST TYPING THE "HIKE"......and then down the sand. Good exercise, to say the least and not as far as I may come off!
$45/night? Naw! That's expensive for a place like this. We don't have the water toys though, so that may change your opinion of the price.
Campfire pits and picnic tables.
One site, a few from me tried to drain their grey with a drain completely clogged with dirt, small leaves and debris. I tried to help them unclog it but it was so deep of dirt, there was no luck getting to use it for the water. Not great maintenance.<//review>

< review>
Very nice area. A large campground  with full hookups except for black tank flush, but they do have a dump station. Campground sites are basically in a parking lot however there's electricity, water, and gray water dump on site.  This campground was very quiet when we are here in early February 2019. A bit pricey though ($40/night). Need to cross the road to get to the lake.<//review>

< Review>
It's a perfect getaway from the big city and it's located like 1hour and 25 min from Los Angeles. They have a lake to visit for the day and also camping grounds. They have two different campgrounds one for people who just want to camp with a tent and another for the RV and we stayed at the RV place without an RV and was 15 dollars more , 45 for RV section and 30 just for tents. But best part about the RV section it has electricity and water. You can come and go as you please the gates always open and staff and park rangers very helpful. It is a walk to the lake though. But the campground have benches, fire pits, restroom and shower. It's very clean too. They allow boats and jet skies on the lake too< /Review>

<review>Always enjoy a day at the lake. Now, since they have inspections of the boats, it doesn't get as full. 0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e</gmap_id>
< review>
I Love this lake. The only thing I don't like is that the bathrooms aren't kept well. My children were saying that one of the stalls in the men's restroom had cobwebs with little spiders, imagine if one bit my son, and there is no soap to wash our hands. What if we're doing the picnic afterwards and we have to use the restrooms? Water isn't enough to clean our hands and eat food afterwards. There are no lifeguards but there are posts for lifeguards. Are there specific dates for them to work? People can be dumb, what if someone starts  drowning. Who's gonna save that person? Another swimmer? What if they start drowning as well just because they tried to be heroes? Sorry but these are the little things that bother me about this wonderful lake. Just thought I'd put it out there. Other than that, the lake is gorgeous.<//review>

<rating>3< /rating>< user>

<response>None< /response><name>JAELYN DOGWATER<//name><pictures>None</pictures><gmapID>0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e< /gmapID>< Time>
1508050994567<//Time>
<text>Ok. No fire pits where we were in group area. Very loud neighbors in the group area next to us, we couldn't sleep over the loud Spanish music and karaoke plus loud people singing and dancing. I can appreciate the fact they were having a great time and probably went here to have the freedom to be loud without complaints but for people like us with friends and families looking for peace and nature quiet it was a bummer. Sometimes it is what it is when you camp. We still liked it. It was clean but they need soap in restrooms for sure. Large group fire pit was awesome. Water and sink was great and handy. Needs more trees for shade. Couldn't see lake at all from camp which was a bummer too. I think there are better local camp locations for groups, we enjoyed lake Hemet. It may be just our particular group site. I will review again after camping in regular spots.< /text></record></dataset><record>
< UserId.>
114391179779126247105< /UserId.>
< Review>
Great alternative to the beach, you don't have to fight for parking, $10 admission per vehicle which is about the same for the beach if you find parking in a reasonable time at the beach.   Bring a canopy and chairs, even saw people bbq'ing it up, which I'll bring mine next time! You don't have to worry about the waves taking your kids away like the beach either, personally I'd rather go here than the beach because the little kids though is definitely hotter but tiki each their own in my opinion, at least the bathrooms didn't smell like you know what, toilet flush is really weak, so hope you don't have a big log to drop off lol going to have to bring a boat or sea doo to experience that another time here.< /Review>

<Text>So i am writing this review because i only came here based on others reviews so hoping mine helps out to. I never ever even heard of perris beach i wanted to take my kids to a beach before summer ends but didnt want to deal with the drive so i googled closest beach to me and perris beach popped up i was like where is this? Read the reviews and said ok lets check it out. Love that its close to us just 30 mins away i didnt have to deal with hours of bumper to bumper traffic to get to the beach. Just $10 to get in per vehicle amazing prices. Brought our own food and drinks what an awesome cheap family fun day without breaking my wallet. We went on a tuesday and it wasnt crowded at all we parked in lot 1. I loved that it wasnt crowded and it was very friendly family people. The water felt amazing and was clean. Life guard was on duty so i felt safe with my kids. My whole family enjoyed being there for 6 hours had so much fun and we will definitely be back we found our new beach place.<//Text><Rating>5</Rating>< GmapID>

< review>
We attended a family reunion here; we were told there would be free parking, if we told the rangers which party we were part of. When we approached the ranger station, the girl working was insistent on us having to pay the park fee.
We had to go through a very difficult process to get our money back. $10 isn't a big deal, but it added up to the park ripping us off hundreds of dollars, due to the amount of people that attended. The station we originally went through said they couldn't refund us, so everyone had to make the long drive to the other station, on the other end of the park.
Very disappointed with the ranger's lack of knowledge & customer service.
We love the park, but won't be planning anymore events here.</review>

< review>
Just finished an 11 mile bike ride in their newly paved bike path. They still have to finish the path on the retrofitted  levy. But this place is great to bring the family. Plenty of parking, picnic tables, restrooms, bbq's, & shade fron the scorching sun. Clean water in the reservoir where you can fish, jet ski, kayak, or whatever you desire involving water sports. For $10 entry let vehicle you can't beat that. Come during the week to miss out on the crowds. You can camp out too if that's your bag.

Think it's time for me to get into paddle boarding.</review>

112959473411376131694</userid>
< user_name>
Greg Zoll<//user_name>
<date>1529881038656< /date>< rating>
4</rating>
< review>
The lake is full! All the ramps are open again and they have the flow of traffic for boats in and out going much better this year.  The marina has a store for the last minute necessities.  If you are camping, make sure you get a reservation and know it's going to take a very long time to check in but it is a nice campground with clean showers and bathrooms.  Note to the wise, if your campsite is vacant the night before you can likely check in early, they opened check-in at noon yesterday, wish we had known!  There will be an extra charge for extra vehicles, the max is 3 per site no exceptions with now overflow lot so if you have more than 3 you will need a second site.  Also, if you have boats, the launch fee is not included in your camping fees.  Book early if you need hooksups, the campground does fill up
We did see lots of sites in tent only loops open.</review>

<username>Tasia Kunhardt<//username><time>1492357162706< /time>< Rate>
1</Rate>
<review>Unless you want to feel like you are camping in Tijuana,  don't camp here. "Noise ordnance" at 10pm that no one enforces. So it's apparently totally okay that 4 different sites are blasting music all night long. No time limit to what time you can show up, so expect to be woken up by people showing up and setting up their camp late at night, and of course they will also blast music and yell to each other, regardless of the time of night. There are no patrols, and no one at the front office to go to at night.Your only option would be to call 911. sites are crammed together and there are no designated walk ways to the restrooms, so people literally just walk through your camp. No patrols means no one enforcing the noise ordnance. My little kids were awake all night. This is our second time, and it was like this both times. We won't be coming back here.< /review>< pics>
None</pics>

<Pictures>None<//Pictures><name>B Mc< /name><gmapID>0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e<//gmapID>< UserId.>
100594382077985641997</UserId.>
<response>None< /response>< date>
1535176623452<//date>
<Text>Underrated lake. Usually not super busy or crowded during the summer, the park has both primitive camping and sites with hookups, and if you have a trailer you will be glad to have the A/C cranked since it gets hot. There are beaches for swimming, a quaint marina with boar rentals and the requisite store, and picnic areas near the shore with green grass(!). There's even a cool island in the middle of the lake you can explore and have a picnic on.
As of August 2018 the water level has risen significantly since repairs to the dam were finished. You can go 35 mph on the lake while dragging your drunk family behind you on an inner tube, while nearly bowling over kayaks and smaller boats. Its not quite as crazy as Lake Elsinore, but expect weekends to be worse. Also, it's not the greatest for bass or other trophy fishing but there are plenty of bluegill, catfish, and smaller fish, and you can fish on the docks for 3$ a day (try live bait). Also, there are no kayak or paddleboard rentals I am aware of, which is definitely a missed oppurtunity.
All in all, this lake is on the rebouund and does not deserve the bad rap that people give it.<//Text><rate>4< /rate></record>

<pics>None</pics><gmap_id>0x80dca0ab76284ae5:0x532c29a35fd7649e<//gmap_id><Response>None</Response>< date>
1535176623452< /date>
< user_id>
100594382077985641997< /user_id>
< username>
B Mc<//username>
< review>
Underrated lake. Usually not super busy or crowded during the summer, the park has both primitive camping and sites with hookups, and if you have a trailer you will be glad to have the A/C cranked since it gets hot. There are beaches for swimming, a quaint marina with boar rentals and the requisite store, and picnic areas near the shore with green grass(!). There's even a cool island in the middle of the lake you can explore and have a picnic on.
As of August 2018 the water level has risen significantly since repairs to the dam were finished. You can go 35 mph on the lake while dragging your drunk family behind you on an inner tube, while nearly bowling over kayaks and smaller boats. Its not quite as crazy as Lake Elsinore, but expect weekends to be worse. Also, it's not the greatest for bass or other trophy fishing but there are plenty of bluegill, catfish, and smaller fish, and you can fish on the docks for 3$ a day (try live bait). Also, there are no kayak or paddleboard rentals I am aware of, which is definitely a missed oppurtunity.
All in all, this lake is on the rebouund and does not deserve the bad rap that people give it.< /review>
< Rate>
4</Rate>
</record></dataset><record>

< text>
I've heard countless negative comments over the years about this lake and it's camping accommodations; the reason it took me twenty years to check it out for myself.

I have to say with few exceptions: the majority of criticisms were inaccurate -- at least when our family visited. The water was clean, the people were friendly and the campsites pass for decent. Trees are a bit thin so take an owning of some sort.

--KL<//text>
